<h2>Bed Bug Tips for Travelers</h2>
<a title="click to view larger image" href="http://www.dshs.state.tx.us/assets/0/76/110/8589934629/8589934646/d14f1ccb-f5a5-457b-8dd2-c1f623c35a17.jpg">
	<img src="http://www.dshs.state.tx.us/assets/0/76/110/8589934629/8589934646/35ff3f71-bbcc-41be-aa48-efab8ce7c1a9.jpg" alt="bed bugs and droppings present on shoe" title="bed bugs and droppings present on shoe"/>
</a>
<div class="small">Click on picture for a larger view<br />Photo courtesy of Lois N Sorkin, BCE</div>
<p>Be careful when you travel.  You can come into contact with bed bugs anywhere.  Here are some tips that may help you while traveling.</p>
<ol>
	<li>Take only what you will need to use for the trip </li>
	<li>Take all toiletries and place them in plastic zip-loc bags and pack additional large kitchen garbage bags to store worn clothes. </li>
	<li>Inspect your hotel room prior to bringing your luggage and belongings into the room. </li>
	<li>Turn back the comforter, sheets and mattress pads and look for bed bug fecal spots, bed bugs, and eggs in seam line of mattresses and between mattress and box springs, behind hanging pictures and headboards. </li>
	<li>Store suitcases on the luggage racks NOT on the floor. </li>
	<li>Worn clothing should be placed in an airtight bag and not in the suitcase. </li>
	<li>Before packing to leave the hotel inspect your luggage for bed bugs and place all personal effects in bags, then in the suitcases. </li>
	<li>When you arrive home, leave your luggage outside -- DO NOT take it into the home if at all possible. </li>
	<li>Remove the items and inspect for bed bugs immediately; wash all clothing in hot water and place in the dryer at the highest heat setting for a minimum of 20 minutes. </li>
	<li>Items that can not be laundered and dried at high heat should be dry-cleaned. </li>
	<li>Place your luggage in tightly sealed plastic bags and leave in the garage if possible.</li>
</ol>

